INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  '6e554ea3-5513-4b47-b14d-5853656f2984',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$Elasticsearch Query Optimization — Profile API, Slow Logs, and Killing N+1 Fetches$escape$,
  $escape$Elasticsearch's Profile API is your EXPLAIN ANALYZE equivalent. Wrap any query in `"profile": true` and you get shard-level timing broken into `build_scorer`, `next_doc`, `match`, and `score` phases. A `build_scorer` time dominating the breakdown usually means a costly script or wildcard leading clause — rewrite with a `terms` filter or a `keyword` field instead.

For persistent visibility, set `index.search.slowlog.threshold.query.warn: 500ms` per index or cluster-wide via `_cluster/settings`. Slow logs surface real traffic patterns Profile can't capture.

The classic Elasticsearch N+1 pattern: fetching a list of IDs from one index, then issuing individual `GET /{index}/_doc/{id}` calls in a loop. Replace with a single `_mget` or a `terms` query with `_source` filtering. For deep pagination, swap `from/size` for `search_after` — `from: 10000` forces Elasticsearch to collect and discard 10k hits on every shard before returning results, destroying latency at scale.$escape$,
  $escape$POST /logs-2024/_search
{
  "profile": true,
  "query": {
    "bool": {
      "filter": [
        { "term": { "level": "error" } },
        { "range": { "@timestamp": { "gte": "now-1h" } } }
      ]
    }
  },
  "search_after": [1712345678000, "doc_id_xyz"],
  "sort": [
    { "@timestamp": "desc" },
    { "_id": "asc" }
  ],
  "size": 50
}$escape$,
  $escape$bash$escape$,
