INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  'a7c21981-ac1b-4465-9df8-81661ab373e3',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$Elasticsearch Data Modeling — Denormalize First, Use Nested and Join Sparingly$escape$,
  $escape$Elasticsearch is document-oriented — denormalization is the default and correct choice for most access patterns. Flattening related data into a single document avoids expensive cross-document lookups and keeps query paths simple.

The trap: plain `object` arrays. Elasticsearch flattens object arrays internally, destroying field correlation. A query for `{color: red, size: L}` will match a doc containing `[{color: red, size: S}, {color: blue, size: L}]` — a silent false positive.

Use `nested` type when you need to query correlated fields within array elements. Each nested object is stored as a hidden Lucene document and queried via `nested` query + `path`. It preserves correctness but increases index size and query overhead.

For true one-to-many where the child side updates frequently and independently, `join` field (parent-child) avoids reindexing the parent on every child update — but carries a ~5–10x query penalty and requires all related docs on the same shard.

Design rule: start fully denormalized, add `nested` when array correlation produces wrong results, reach for `join` only when child update frequency makes reindexing the parent prohibitive.$escape$,
  $escape$GET /products/_search
{
  "query": {
    "nested": {
      "path": "variants",
      "query": {
        "bool": {
          "must": [
            { "term": { "variants.color": "red" } },
            { "term": { "variants.size": "S" } }
          ]
        }
      }
    }
  }
}$escape$,
  $escape$bash$escape$,
